Filter and Prepare Data

# Include both treatment (predictable == 1) and control (control == 1) groups
data_analysis <- data %>%
  mutate(
    # Create treatment group labels
    group_label = case_when(
      control == 1 ~ "Control",
      predictable == 1 & period == 0 ~ "Baseline",
      predictable == 1 & draw == "H" ~ "High Draw",
      predictable == 1 & draw == "L" ~ "Low Draw",
      TRUE ~ "Unknown"
    ),
    high_draw = ifelse(draw == "H", 1, 0),
    period_label = case_when(
      period == 0 ~ "Period 0 (Baseline)",
      TRUE ~ paste0("Period ", period)
    )
  )

cat("Dataset with treatment and control groups:\n")
cat("  Total observations:", nrow(data_analysis), "\n")
cat("  Unique households:", length(unique(data_analysis$hh_id)), "\n")
cat("  Periods included:", sort(unique(data_analysis$period)), "\n\n")

# Summary of observations by period and group
cat("Observations by period and group:\n")
data_analysis %>%
  count(period, group_label) %>%
  arrange(period, group_label) %>%
  print()

# Summary by treatment status
cat("\n\nSummary by treatment status:\n")
data_analysis %>%
  group_by(predictable, control) %>%
  summarise(n = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  print()

VISUALIZATION: OUTCOMES BY PERIOD

Mental Health Outcomes Over Time

# Mental health outcomes
mh_data <- data_analysis %>%
  group_by(period, group_label) %>%
  summarise(
    depression = mean(phq2_z, na.rm = TRUE),
    anxiety = mean(gad2_z, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  filter(group_label != "Unknown")

p_depression <- ggplot(mh_data, aes(x = period, y = depression, color = group_label)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray50", alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Baseline" = "#FF9800",
                                "High Draw" = "#2E7D32",
                                "Low Draw" = "#C62828",
                                "Control" = "#1976D2")) +
  labs(
    title = "Depression (PHQ-2) Over Time",
    x = "Period",
    y = "Depression Score (standardized)",
    color = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

p_anxiety <- ggplot(mh_data, aes(x = period, y = anxiety, color = group_label)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, linetype = "dashed", color = "gray50", alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Baseline" = "#FF9800",
                                "High Draw" = "#2E7D32",
                                "Low Draw" = "#C62828",
                                "Control" = "#1976D2")) +
  labs(
    title = "Anxiety (GAD-2) Over Time",
    x = "Period",
    y = "Anxiety Score (standardized)",
    color = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

p_depression + p_anxiety +
  plot_annotation(
    title = "Mental Health Trajectories by Period",
    subtitle = "Treatment Groups (High/Low Draw) vs Control Group (Periods 0-6)",
    theme = theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14))
  )

Note: Mental health is measured using standardized PHQ-2 (depression) and GAD-2 (anxiety) scales. Lower scores indicate better mental health. The control group (blue) received no cash transfers throughout the study. The baseline period (period 0, orange) shows pre-treatment outcomes for the treatment group before randomization into high or low draw schedules. Comparing treatment groups to control helps identify whether cash transfers improved mental health outcomes.

Income with vs.without Study Payments

income_comp_data <- data_analysis %>%

    theme = theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14))
  )

Note: This comparison shows the total resources available to households including versus excluding the experimental study payments. With Study Payments (total_income_99_w_study) includes all income sources: study income from the experiment, labor income, agricultural income, and other sources. Without Study Payments (total_income_99) excludes the experimental transfers, showing only naturally occurring household income. The difference between these measures reveals the direct income boost from the cash transfer experiment and helps identify whether households use study income to substitute for (reduce) other income-generating activities, or whether it represents pure additional resources. The control group provides a counterfactual showing what income would have been without any experimental intervention.

Labor income includes wages from employment and self-employment activities. Crop sales income captures revenue from selling agricultural crops. Other agricultural income includes sales from livestock, poultry, eggs, milk, and other farm products not captured in crop sales. Comparing these income streams reveals how households economic activities and income portfolios evolve in response to the experimental transfers, including potential substitution effects (e.g., reducing labor supply when receiving transfers) or complementarity effects (e.g., using transfers to invest in agricultural production).

Financial Position Over Time

Note: Financial position tracks household savings and debt dynamics. Savings flow measures the net change in savings during a period (positive = accumulating, negative = drawing down savings). Current savings shows the stock of liquid savings held at the time of the survey. Outstanding loans captures total debt owed across all sources (formal lenders, informal lenders, family/friends). New loans taken counts the number of loans initiated in the period. Positive savings flow and declining debt indicate improving financial security, while the opposite pattern may signal financial stress or strategic use of credit. Comparing to control groups reveals whether cash transfers improve household financial resilience.

  )

Note: Cash inflow includes all money coming into the household (study income, labor income, agricultural sales, asset sales, loans taken, etc.). Cash outflow includes all money leaving the household (consumption, loan payments, asset purchases, etc.). Positive savings flow occurs when inflow exceeds outflow.

Note: Adult Equivalent (AE) measures adjust for household composition using standard equivalence scales. This controls for differences in household size and age composition, providing a more accurate comparison of living standards across households. For example, a household with 4 adults and 2 children has a higher AE than a household with 2 adults. Income and consumption per AE show the resources available to each equivalent adult in the household.

asset_data <- data_analysis %>%

Note: Asset dynamics capture household investment and coping strategies. Positive net asset position (sales > purchases) may indicate distress selling or portfolio rebalancing, while negative values (purchases > sales) indicate asset accumulation. Livestock transactions are particularly important in rural contexts as they represent both savings vehicles and productive assets. Durable goods include items like furniture, appliances, and equipment. The dotted horizontal line at zero helps identify periods of net accumulation (below zero) versus net depletion (above zero).

Note: Labor supply captures household work effort. Days worked is the total number of days any household member worked for pay during the recall period. Working adults counts the number of adults in the household who engaged in income-generating work. Changes in labor supply may reflect both income effects (working less when cash transfers are received) and substitution effects (reallocating time to other activities). Household composition variables (number of children, household size) may change over time due to births, deaths, or migration, affecting both labor supply and consumption needs. ```
